{"id": "8270", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=8270", "title": "December 25", "text": "December 25\n\nBULLET::::- 274 – A temple for Sol Invictus is dedicated in Rome by Emperor Aurelian.\nBULLET::::- 333 – Roman Emperor Constantine the Great elevates his youngest son Constans to the rank of \"Caesar\".\nBULLET::::- 336 – First documentary sign of Christmas celebration in Rome.\nBULLET::::- 350 – Vetranio meets Constantius II at Naissus (Serbia) and is forced to abdicate his title (Caesar). Constantius allows him to live as a private citizen on a state pension.\nBULLET::::- 508 – Clovis I, king of the Franks, is baptized into the Catholic faith at Reims, by Saint Remigius.\nBULLET::::- 597 – Augustine of Canterbury and his fellow-labourers baptise in Kent more than 10,000 Anglo-Saxons.\nBULLET::::- 800 – The coronation of Charlemagne as Holy Roman Emperor, in Rome.\nBULLET::::- 1000 – The foundation of the Kingdom of Hungary: Hungary is established as a Christian kingdom by Stephen I of Hungary.\nBULLET::::- 1013 – Sweyn Forkbeard takes control of the Danelaw and is proclaimed king of England.\nBULLET::::- 1025 – Coronation of Mieszko II Lambert as king of Poland.\nBULLET::::- 1066 – William the Conqueror, Duke of Normandy is crowned king of England, at Westminster Abbey, London.\nBULLET::::- 1076 – Coronation of Bolesław II the Generous as king of Poland.\nBULLET::::- 1100 – Baldwin of Boulogne is crowned the first King of Jerusalem in the Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem.\nBULLET::::- 1130 – Count Roger II of Sicily is crowned the first king of Sicily.\nBULLET::::- 1261 – Eleven-year-old John IV Laskaris of the restored Eastern Roman Empire is deposed and blinded by orders of his co-ruler Michael VIII Palaiologos.\nBULLET::::- 1492 – The carrack \"Santa María\", commanded by Christopher Columbus, runs onto a reef off Haiti due to an improper watch.\nBULLET::::- 1553 – Battle of Tucapel: Mapuche rebels under Lautaro defeat the Spanish conquistadors and executes the governor of Chile, Pedro de Valdivia.\nBULLET::::- 1559 – Pope Pius IV is elected.\nBULLET::::- 1758 – Halley's Comet is sighted by Johann Georg Palitzsch, confirming Edmund Halley's prediction of its passage. This was the first passage of a comet predicted ahead of time.\nBULLET::::- 1776 – George Washington and the Continental Army cross the Delaware River at night to attack Hessian forces serving Great Britain at Trenton, New Jersey, the next day.\nBULLET::::- 1793 – General \"Mad Anthony\" Wayne and a 300 man detachment identify the site of St. Clair's 1791 defeat by the large number of unburied human remains at modern Fort Recovery, Ohio.\nBULLET::::- 1809 – Dr. Ephraim McDowell performs the first ovariotomy, removing a 22-pound tumor.\nBULLET::::- 1814 – Rev. Samuel Marsden holds the first Christian service on land in New Zealand at Rangihoua Bay.\nBULLET::::- 1815 – The Handel and Haydn Society, oldest continually performing arts organization in the United States, gives its first performance.\nBULLET::::- 1826 – The Eggnog Riot at the United States Military Academy concludes after beginning the previous evening.\nBULLET::::- 1831 – The Great Jamaican Slave Revolt begins; up to 20% of Jamaica's slaves mobilize in an ultimately unsuccessful fight for freedom.\nBULLET::::- 1837 – Second Seminole War: American general Zachary Taylor leads 1,100 troops against the Seminoles at the Battle of Lake Okeechobee.\nBULLET::::- 1868 – Pardons for ex-Confederates: United States President Andrew Johnson grants an unconditional pardon to all Confederate veterans.\nBULLET::::- 1914 – A series of unofficial truces occur across the Western Front to celebrate Christmas.\nBULLET::::- 1932 – A magnitude 7.6 earthquake in Gansu, China kills 275 people.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – Admiral Chester W. Nimitz arrives at Pearl Harbor to assume command of the U.S. Pacific Fleet\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: Battle of Hong Kong ends, beginning the Japanese occupation of Hong Kong.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – Admiral Émile Muselier seizes the archipelago of Saint Pierre and Miquelon, which become the first part of France to be liberated by the Free French Forces.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – The first European self-sustaining nuclear chain reaction is initiated within the Soviet Union's F-1 nuclear reactor.\nBULLET::::- 1950 – The Stone of Scone, traditional coronation stone of British monarchs, is taken from Westminster Abbey by Scottish nationalist students. It later turns up in Scotland on April 11, 1951.\nBULLET::::- 1951 – A bomb explodes at the home of Harry T. Moore and Harriette V. S. Moore, early leaders of the Civil Rights Movement, killing Harry instantly and fatally wounding Harriette.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – The Soviet Union conducts its final above-ground nuclear weapon test, in anticipation of the 1963 Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – Turkish Cypriot Bayrak Radio begins transmitting in Cyprus after Turkish Cypriots are forcibly excluded from Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation.\nBULLET::::- 1968 – Apollo program: \"Apollo 8\" performs the very first successful Trans-Earth injection (TEI) maneuver, sending the crew and spacecraft on a trajectory back to Earth from Lunar orbit.\nBULLET::::- 1968 – Kilvenmani massacre: Forty-four Dalits (untouchables) are burnt to death in Kizhavenmani village, Tamil Nadu, a retaliation for a campaign for higher wages by Dalit laborers.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin meets in Egypt with its president Anwar Sadat.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – Romanian Revolution: Deposed President of Romania Nicolae Ceaușescu and his wife, Elena, are condemned to death and executed after a summary trial.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – Mikhail Gorbachev resigns as President of the Soviet Union (the union itself is dissolved the next day). Ukraine's referendum is finalized and Ukraine officially leaves the Soviet Union.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – UTAGE Flight 141, a Boeing 727-223, crashes at the Cotonou Airport in Benin, killing 151 people.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – The ill-fated \"Beagle 2\" probe, released from the Mars Express spacecraft on December 19, stops transmitting shortly before its scheduled landing.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – The Cassini orbiter releases Huygens probe which successfully landed on Saturn's moon Titan on January 14, 2005.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – An Antonov An-72 plane crashes close to the city of Shymkent, killing 27 people.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – A Russian Defence Ministry Tupolev Tu-154 carrying members of the Alexandrov Ensemble crashes into the Black Sea shortly after takeoff, killing all 92 people on board.\n\nBULLET::::- 1250 – John IV Laskaris, Byzantine emperor (d. 1305)\nBULLET::::- 1281 – Alice de Lacy, 4th Countess of Lincoln (d. 1348)\nBULLET::::- 1400 – John Sutton, 1st Baron Dudley, Lord Lieutenant of Ireland (d. 1487)\nBULLET::::- 1424 – Margaret Stewart, Dauphine of France (d. 1445)\nBULLET::::- 1461 – Christina of Saxony, Queen consort of Denmark (d. 1521)\nBULLET::::- 1490 – Francesco Marinoni, Italian Roman Catholic priest (d. 1562)\nBULLET::::- 1493 – Antoinette de Bourbon, French noblewoman (d. 1583)\nBULLET::::- 1505 – Christine of Saxony, German noblewoman (d. 1549)\nBULLET::::- 1564 – Johannes Buxtorf, German Calvinist theologian (d. 1629)\nBULLET::::- 1583 – Orlando Gibbons, English organist and composer (d. 1625)\nBULLET::::- 1584 – Margaret of Austria, Queen of Spain (d. 1611)\nBULLET::::- 1601 – Ernest I, Duke of Saxe-Gotha (d. 1675)\nBULLET::::- 1628 – Noël Coypel, French painter and educator (d. 1707)\nBULLET::::- 1642 (OS) – Isaac Newton, English physicist and mathematician (d. 1726/1727)\nBULLET::::- 1652 – Archibald Pitcairne, Scottish physician, anatomist, and scholar (d. 1713)\nBULLET::::- 1665 – Lady Grizel Baillie, Scottish-English poet and songwriter (d. 1746)\nBULLET::::- 1674 – Thomas Halyburton, Scottish minister and theologian (d. 1712)\nBULLET::::- 1686 – Giovanni Battista Somis, Italian violinist and composer (d. 1763)\nBULLET