{"id": "8334", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=8334", "title": "December 18", "text": "December 18\n\nBULLET::::- 218 BC – Second Punic War: Battle of the Trebia: Hannibal's Carthaginian forces defeat those of the Roman Republic.\nBULLET::::- 1271 – Kublai Khan renames his empire \"Yuan\" (元 yuán), officially marking the start of the Yuan dynasty of Mongolia and China.\nBULLET::::- 1499 – A rebellion breaks out in Alpujarras in response to the forced conversions of Muslims in Spain.\nBULLET::::- 1622 – Portuguese forces score a military victory over the Kingdom of Kongo at the Battle of Mbumbi in present-day Angola.\nBULLET::::- 1655 – The Whitehall Conference ends with the determination that there was no law preventing Jews from re-entering England after the Edict of Expulsion of 1290.\nBULLET::::- 1777 – The United States celebrates its first Thanksgiving, marking the recent victory by the American rebels over British General John Burgoyne at Saratoga in October.\nBULLET::::- 1787 – New Jersey becomes the third state to ratify the U.S. Constitution.\nBULLET::::- 1793 – Surrender of the frigate \"La Lutine\" by French Royalists to Lord Samuel Hood; renamed , she later becomes a famous treasure wreck.\nBULLET::::- 1833 – The national anthem of the Russian Empire, \"God Save the Tsar!\", is first performed.\nBULLET::::- 1854 – The Legislative Assembly of the Province of Canada abolishes the seigneurial system.\nBULLET::::- 1865 – US Secretary of State William Seward proclaims the adoption of the Thirteenth Amendment, prohibiting slavery throughout the USA.\nBULLET::::- 1878 – The Al-Thani family become the rulers of the state of Qatar.\nBULLET::::- 1892 – Premiere performance of \"The Nutcracker\" by Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky in Saint Petersburg, Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1898 – Gaston de Chasseloup-Laubat sets the first officially recognized land speed record of in a Jeantaud electric car.\nBULLET::::- 1900 – The Upper Ferntree Gully to Gembrook, Victoria Narrow-gauge (2 ft 6 in or 762 mm) Railway (now the Puffing Billy Railway) in Victoria, Australia is opened for traffic.\nBULLET::::- 1916 – World War I: The Battle of Verdun ends when German forces under Chief of staff Erich von Falkenhayn are defeated by the French, and suffer 337,000 casualties.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – The resolution containing the language of the Eighteenth Amendment to enact Prohibition is passed by the United States Congress.\nBULLET::::- 1932 – The Chicago Bears defeat the Portsmouth Spartans in the first NFL playoff game to win the NFL Championship.\nBULLET::::- 1935 – The Lanka Sama Samaja Party is founded in Ceylon.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – World War II: The Battle of the Heligoland Bight, the first major air battle of the war, takes place.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – World War II: Seventy-seven B-29 Superfortress and 200 other aircraft of U.S. Fourteenth Air Force bomb Hankow, China, a Japanese supply base.\nBULLET::::- 1958 – Project SCORE, the world's first communications satellite, is launched.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – Saturn's moon Epimetheus is discovered by astronomer Richard Walker.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Vietnam War: President Richard Nixon announces that the United States will engage North Vietnam in Operation Linebacker II, a series of Christmas bombings, after peace talks collapsed with North Vietnam on the 13th.\nBULLET::::- 1973 – Soviet Soyuz Programme: \"Soyuz 13\", crewed by cosmonauts Valentin Lebedev and Pyotr Klimuk, is launched from Baikonur in the Soviet Union.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – United Airlines Flight 2860 crashes near Kaysville, Utah, killing all three crew members on board.\nBULLET::::- 1981 – First flight of the Russian heavy strategic bomber Tu-160, the world's largest combat aircraft, largest supersonic aircraft and largest variable-sweep wing aircraft built.\nBULLET::::- 1999 – NASA launches into orbit the Terra platform carrying five Earth Observation instruments, including ASTER, CERES, MISR, MODIS and MOPITT.\nBULLET::::- 2002 – California gubernatorial recall: Then Governor of California Gray Davis announces that the state would face a record budget deficit of $35 billion, roughly double the figure reported during his reelection campaign one month earlier.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – The Chadian Civil War begins when rebel groups, allegedly backed by neighbouring Sudan, launch an attack in Adré.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – The first of a series of floods strikes Malaysia. The death toll of all flooding is at least 118, with over 400,000 people displaced.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – United Arab Emirates holds its first-ever elections.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – Kellingley Colliery, the last deep coal mine in Great Britain, closes.\nBULLET::::- 2017 – Amtrak Cascades passenger train 501, derailed near DuPont, Washington, a city in United States near Olympia, Washington killing six people, and injuring 70 others.\nBULLET::::- 2018 – List of bolides: A meteor exploded over the Bering Sea with a force over 10 times greater than the atomic bomb that destroyed Hiroshima in 1945.\nBULLET::::- 2019 – The United States President Donald Trump is impeached by the United States House of Representatives, becoming the third president of the United States to be impeached.\n\nBULLET::::- 1406 – Richard Olivier de Longueil, French Roman Catholic bishop and cardinal (d. 1470)\nBULLET::::- 1499 – Sebald Heyden, German musicologist and theologian (d. 1561)\nBULLET::::- 1481 – Sophie of Mecklenburg, Duchess of Mecklenburg, Duchess of Saxony (d. 1503)\nBULLET::::- 1505 – Philipp von Hutten, German explorer (d. 1546)\nBULLET::::- 1507 – Ōuchi Yoshitaka, Japanese daimyō (d. 1551)\nBULLET::::- 1552 – Ahmad Ibn al-Qadi, Moroccan writer, judge and mathematician (d. 1616)\nBULLET::::- 1590 – William Louis, Count of Nassau-Saarbrücken (d. 1640)\nBULLET::::- 1602 – Simonds d'Ewes, English historian and politician (d. 1650)\nBULLET::::- 1610 – Charles du Fresne, sieur du Cange, French philologist and historian (d. 1688)\nBULLET::::- 1620 – Heinrich Roth, Ge